      <h3>Design Principles that Guide mCODE Development</h3>
      <p class="lead">If additional specialties follow these, that are more likely to be interoperable and compatible as part of a life-time patient Standard Health Record</p>
      
      <h4>Design Principles</h4>

      <ol>
        <li><b>Community and Use Case</b> driven, with <b>adoption</b> and <b>value</b> a focus from the beginning.
          <ul>
            <li>Need broadest possible support of patients, providers, Gov’t, vendors, payers, etc.</li>
            <li>Ensure standards are informed by and address real community problems. Plan from the start for implementation, adoption and real value.</li>
            <li>Demonstrate potential value in the real environments.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Standardized <b>data</b> is part of the <b>standard of health care</b>. Thus, the primary focus is collection and sharing of quality, core data related to <b>patient care and outcomes</b>, with goal of a lifetime Standard Health Record.
          <ul>
            <li>Data originally collected for one health state can be important for future states.</li>
            <li>Secondary uses of patient care data (personal, research, quality measurement, payer operations, etc.) will be hugely valuable and more cost-effective than current approaches.</li>
            <li>Can also create supplemental IGs.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li><b>Encounter-based</b> and <b>discrete</b> observations and actions (e.g. patient birth date = 11/04/1989 vs. patient is 34 years old).
          <ul>
            <li>Allows aggregated calculations using different observations and actions, via different approaches, for different use cases, at different times.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li><b>Data collected once</b> (generally around the encounter). Data collected can then be reused for multiple use cases going forward.
          <ul>
            <li>Not all data elements will be collected for every patient during every encounter, since people and their disease states differ.</li>
            <li>When data should be collected, the standard provides the template.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Define <b>core clinical data elements</b> needed across key use cases and stakeholders.
          <ul>
            <li>Create supplemental IGs for details important for very specialized situations.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Ensure <b>consistent representation</b> of data elements that may be used across specialties.
          <ul>
            <li>Different specialties require similar data that might have been historically described differently.</li>
            <li>Establish principles, templates and processes that reconcile differences and consolidate in one place, where possible.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Leverage <b>Government-backed interoperability standards</b> whenever possible (e.g., FHIR, USCDI represented in FHIR as US Core, USCDI+ ...).
          <ul>
            <li>Gov’t support increases impetuous for adoption and thus provides a stronger basis for cross-specialty interoperability.</li>
            <li>May require changes to representations of previous work.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Leverage the <b>best available work</b> (standards, tools, etc.).
          <ul>
            <li>If previous work is already represented in Government backed standards, use rather than re-do.</li>
            <li>Leverage the available approaches and tools for modeling and IG development.</li>
            <li>These will motivate higher-quality FHIR IGs that are more coherent across specialties, use cases and projects.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Leverage <b>global code systems</b>.
          <ul>
            <li>Observations and actions are represented consistently within and across specialties, in many cases, around the world.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>Review through <b>clinical specialists and patients first</b>, then other medical, standards and vendor experts.
          <ul>
            <li>Ensure clinical relevance first.</li>
            <li>Add other health use case, technical, and standards expertise.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li>These are data standards for data <b>collection</b> (storage) and <b>exchange, not</b> for user <b>interfaces</b>.
          <ul>
            <li>Systems can be created to present data subsets, and understandable interfaces related to collect, use and analysis for patients, providers and other.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li><b>Controlled by the patient</b>.
          <ul>
            <li>Consent: who gets what data for what purposes for what timeframes in a way that follows the data.</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
<br>
